{
  "title": "__future__ Standard Library Module in Python 3.12+",
  "summary": "This explainer provides an in-depth look at the __future__ standard library module in Python 3.12+, its purpose, usage, and key features.",

  "key_points": [
    "The __future__ module allows developers to use experimental or enhanced features from upcoming Python versions in their current Python code.",
    "It is not a separate module but rather a built-in part of the Python standard library.",
    "Using the __future__ module, you can take advantage of new language constructs and features before they are officially supported by the Python version you're currently using.",
    "Python 3.12+ introduces several new directives within the __future__ module for additional functionality."
  ],

  "code_examples": [
    {
      "language": "python",
      "code": "from __future__ import annotations\n# Example of using 'annotations' future import"
    },
    {
      "language": "python",
      "code": "from __future__ import types_and_staticmethods\n# Example of using 'types_and_staticmethods' future import"
    },
    {
      "language": "python",
      "code": "from __future__ import generators\n# Example of using 'generators' future import"
    }
  ],

  "version_notes": [
    "Python 3.12+ introduces new directives within the __future__ module, such as annotations, types_and_staticmethods, generators, and division.",
    "For a complete list of available directives, refer to the official Python documentation: https://docs.python.org/3/library/__future__.html"
  ],

  "caveats": [
    "While using __future__ can help you use new features earlier, it's important to keep in mind that some experimental features may still be unstable or under development.",
    "It's always a good idea to test your code thoroughly and ensure compatibility with both the current Python version and the __future__ directives you're using."
  ]
}
